ğŸ“– Lesson Content
â€¢ What the Record Is ğŸ“¦ â€” FRAP 10(a): the original papers and exhibits filed in the district court, the transcript of proceedings, and the docket entries.
â€¢ Transcripts ğŸ§ â€” FRAP 10(b): order necessary parts within the time set by rule (often 14 days after the Notice of Appeal). If ordering less than the whole transcript, file a Statement of the Issues to be raised so the appellee can add needed portions.
â€¢ No Transcript? Make One ğŸ“ â€” FRAP 10(c): prepare a statement of the evidence or proceedings from the best available means; serve it, and have it settled and approved by the district court.
â€¢ Agreed Statement ğŸ¤ â€” FRAP 10(d): the parties may prepare an agreed statement as the record on appeal instead of the full record.
â€¢ Correcting Omissions ğŸ§© â€” FRAP 10(e): correct or supplement the record by stipulation, by the district court, or by the court of appeals to ensure accuracy.
â€¢ Forwarding the Record ğŸšš â€” FRAP 11: the district clerk forwards the record; you still must monitor completeness and move promptly to fix gaps.
